### ||| AUTO 754 - وعن سعيد بن الحارث أنه سأل جابرا رضي الله عنه عن
~~الوضوء مما مست النار . فقال : لا قد كنا زمن النبي صلى الله عليه وسلم لا
~~نجد مثل ذلك الطعام إلا قليلا فإذا نحن وجدناه لم يكن لنا مناديل إلا أكفنا
~~وسواعدنا وأقدامنا ثم نصلي ولا نتوضأ . رواه البخاري
# 754. Sa`id bin Al-Harith reported: I asked Jabir (May Allah be pleased
~~with him) whether it was obligatory to make Wudu' for Salat (prayer)
~~after eating cooked food. He said: "No, because in the lifetime of
~~Messenger of Allah (PBUH), such food was rarely available. We had no
~~handkerchiefs, so when we ate such food we would wipe our fingers
~~against our palms, forearms or (the sole of our) feet, and would offer
~~Salat without fresh Wudu' (for prayer).''
# [Al-Bukhari].
# Commentary: There are three points in this Hadith. First, the life of
~~the Companions was simple, divested of all kinds of luxuries and
~~comforts. They lived on whatever was available to them. Second, a man's
~~ablution is not nullified by eating a cooked food. In the early days of
~~Islam, this command was put into practice but later it was cancelled.
~~Third, if a handkerchief, or a towel or water is not available, a man
~~can (after taking a meal) clean his mouth and hands with his palms and
~~wrists so that his clothes will not be smeared during Salat (prayer).
PageV01P958
